s fluid","Concentration of sperm cells"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe rete testis is a network of interconnected channels located in the mediastinum testis. Its primary function is to collect and transport sperm from the seminiferous tubules to the efferent ductules.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of sperm\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the seminiferous tubules through spermatogenesis. The \u003Cstrong\u003Etransport of sperm\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct function of the rete testis, which acts as a collecting system. \u003Cstrong\u003EStorage of mature sperm\u003C/strong\u003E occurs primarily in the epididymis. \u003Cstrong\u003ESecretion of seminiferous fluid\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by Sertoli cells within the seminiferous tubules. \u003Cstrong\u003EConcentration of sperm cells\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the epididymis through fluid reabsorption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The rete testis is a network of channels that collects and transports sperm from the seminiferous tubules to the efferent ductules","The rete testis does not produce, store, or mature sperm, nor does it produce seminiferous fluid"],"references":["Tiwana MS, Leslie SW. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis: Testes. [Updated 2023 Apr 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470201/","Benzi TC, Logsdon NT, Sampaio FJB, Favorito LA. Testicular arteries anatomy applied to fowler-sthephens surgery in high undescended testis - a narrative review. Int Braz J Urol. 2022 Jan-Feb;48(1):8-17. doi: 10.1590/S1677-5538.IBJU.2021.99.11. PMID: 34003614; PMCID: PMC8691233","Gurung P, Yetiskul E, Jialal I. Physiology, Male Reproductive System. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538429/","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47991"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15774"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47991"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T22:47:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T22:48:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8465"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62544"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4934"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Reproductive System (Male)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:3